- **Bounded memory**: Add a periodic rebuild phase or use LRU eviction for rarely-active user_ids
- **Distributed extension**: Partition by user_id hash across nodes, aggregate partial results

## Why This Question Is Asked
This problem evaluates the ability to extend classic DP patterns (like the staircase problem) with an additional resource dimension, while also testing space optimization skills and recursive thinking via memoization. It distinguishes candidates who understand both bottom-up and top-down approaches, and who reason through edge cases systematically.

## Key Concepts
- DP with an extra budget constraint (two-dimensional state: position + accumulated cost)
- Space optimization using rolling arrays to reduce O(n·B) space to O(B)
- Memoization on composite state (i, b) for the recursive variant
- Correct base case handling when starting from a virtual position before index 0

## Code Example
```javascript
const MOD = 1_000_000_007n;

function countWays(cost, B) {
  const n = cost.length;
  if (n === 0) return 0;

  // bottom-up with rolling arrays
  let prev2 = new Array(B + 1).fill(0);
  let prev1 = new Array(B + 1).fill(0);

  // base: step 0
  if (cost[0] <= B) prev2[cost[0]] = 1;

  // base: step 1
  if (n > 1 && cost[1] <= B) prev1[cost[1]] = 1;

  // step 2 onwards
  for (let i = 2; i < n; i++) {
    const cur = new Array(B + 1).fill(0);
    for (let b = cost[i]; b <= B; b++) {
      cur[b] = (prev1[b - cost[i]] + prev2[b - cost[i]]) % MOD;
    }
    prev2 = prev1;
    prev1 = cur;
  }

  return n === 1 ? prev2[B] : prev1[B];
}

// memoized DFS variant
function countWaysDFS(cost, B) {
  const n = cost.length;
  const memo = new Map();

  function dfs(i, b) {
    if (b < 0) return 0;
    if (i < 0) return b === 0 ? 1 : 0;
    const key = `${i},${b}`;
    if (memo.has(key)) return memo.get(key);
    const result = (dfs(i - 1, b - cost[i]) + dfs(i - 2, b - cost[i])) % MOD;
    memo.set(key, result);
    return result;
  }

  return dfs(n - 1, B);
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a DP over partitions using prefix sums and a hashmap to achieve linear-time partition counting. This also exercises both bottom-up and top-down reasoning, and edge-case handling for K and negative numbers.

## Key Concepts

- Prefix sums
- Hash map DP
- Edge-case handling (K=0, negative numbers)

## Code Example

```javascript
function countPartitions(A, K) {
  const MOD = 1000000007;
  const N = A.length;
  const prefix = new Array(N+1).fill(0);
  for (let i = 1; i <= N; i++) prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + A[i-1];
  const dp = new Array(N+1).fill(0);
  dp[0] = 1;
  const map = new Map();
  map.set(0, 1);
  for (let i = 1; i <= N; i++) {
    const key = prefix[i] - K;
    const ways = map.get(key) ?? 0;
    dp[i] = ways;
    const cur = (map.get(prefix[i]) ?? 0) + dp[i];
    map.set(prefix[i], cur % MOD);
  }
  return dp[N] % MOD;
}
``` 

